{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473782"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2765"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2765"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.65,0.08,0.03,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96787"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2765"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2765"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79402"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"3622"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5002"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"5993"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45014"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96787"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old Indigenous boy from a remote Australian community presents to a GP as he is in town for the weekend. He has had a 5 day history of lethargy, fevers and pain in his right knee, both wrists and both elbows.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA similar event occurred several months ago, where he had fevers and sore joints. This resolved over 1 week and he never sought medical attention. He is sexually active with 2 female partners in the past 6 months, with infrequent use of barrier protection. He denies any dysuria, genital warts, rashes or pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable, the above named joints are tender and warm but not swollen, and a healing crusted rash is noted over his lower legs. When asked about the rash he states it began over a month ago and looked infected but resolved on its own. His vitals signs are pulse rate 123/min, RR 15/min, temperature 38.6\u02daC, SpO2 99% on room air, and blood pressure 108/74mmHg. Examination of the ears, nose and throat is normal. There is a pansystolic murmur and the lungs are clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reactive arthritis","Acute rheumatic fever","Bacterial endocarditis","Juvenile idiopathic arthritis","Gonococcal arthritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy has \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute rheumatic fever \u003C/strong\u003Ewith the cardinal symptoms of migrating polyarthritis, fever, carditis (systolic murmur is likely a mitral valvulitis) and previous group A streptococcus (GAS) skin infection the likely source. Rarer symptoms include Erythema marginatum, Sydenham chorea and subcutaneous nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Jones criteria (below - with criteria bolded if present in this case) is used to diagnose acute rheumatic fever. It requires a history of streptococcal infection plus either 2 major, or 1 major and 2 minor criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMajor criteria:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolyarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarditis\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENodules\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESydenham chorea\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMinor criteria:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFever\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERaised CRP/ESR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArthralgias\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPR prolongation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis boy is at risk of future episodes of ARF and progression to rheumatic heart disease, and will require regular benzathine penicillin G intramuscular injections to prevent this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReactive arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E classically has the triad of arthritis, conjunctivitis and urethritis in an inflammatory response following a sexually transmitted infection or gastrointestinal infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a complication after previous episodes of rheumatic fever. It causes infected vegetations to form on the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESystemic onset polyarticular \u003Cstrong\u003Ejuvenile idiopathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E can explain his fever and arthritis, however the new onset heart murmur and his history of likely streptococcal skin infection makes ARF most likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated gonococcal infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause dermatitis-arthritis syndrome with dermatitis, polyarthritis, tenosynovitis and constitutional symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute rheumatic fever is an autoimmune inflammatory response to GAS infection.","Treating acute rheumatic fever with regular long term benzathine penicillin injections is crucial to prevent progression to rheumatic heart disease."],"references":["Carapetis JR, Beaton A, Cunningham MW, Guilherme L, Karthikeyan G, Mayosi BM, Sable C, Steer A, Wilson N, Wyber R, Z\u00fchlke L. Acute rheumatic fever and rheumatic heart disease. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Jan 14;2:15084. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2015.84. PMID: 27188830; PMCID: PMC5810582. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27188830/","Alqanatish J, Alfadhel A, Albelali A, Alqahtani D. Acute rheumatic fever diagnosis and management: Review of the global implications of the new revised diagnostic criteria with a focus on Saudi Arabia. J Saudi Heart Assoc. 2019 Oct;31(4):273-281. doi: 10.1016/j.jsha.2019.07.002. Epub 2019 Aug 13. PMID: 31516307; PMCID: PMC6734099. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6734099/","Chowdhury MDS, Koziatek CA, Rajnik M. Acute Rheumatic Fever. 2023 Aug 2. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 37603629. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37603629/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79402"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2765"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79402"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:59:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T21:59:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2765"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96787"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attribut